      "issues": [
        {
          "code": "valence_giveaway",
          "distractor_index": null,
          "note": "The prior valence defect is repaired in form but not in substance. All three distractors now mention desire/motivation, but every one points AWAY from selling (wait for a higher offer / keep the property / renovate before selling) while the key is the only sell-now option ('desire to cash out'). This deck teaches distance-equals-cash-out in multiple cards (ch02-053, ch02-064, ch02-067), so a test-wise learner answers by picking the lone sell-direction option without knowing the mechanism. At least one distractor must share the key's pro-sale valence with a wrong mechanism (e.g., distance increases desire to sell because the home sits vacant and loses value)."
        },
        {
          "code": "style_mismatch",
          "distractor_index": null,
          "note": "Secondary: the three distractors are word-for-word template clones of each other ('It increases the owner's X, strengthening their desire to Y') while the key uses a different construction ('It makes managing the property a headache, increasing their desire to cash out'), making the key the structural odd-one-out — the same form-isolation defect flagged on ch02-055 last round."
        },
        {
          "code": "ambiguous_correctness",
          "distractor_index": null,
          "note": "Checker escalation after three failed authoring rounds: the lesson teaches the key from multiple angles, so any in-lesson distractor is either eliminable or partially true. Needs human authoring or a different question form."
        }
      ]
